and device_ids associated with that resolved_id...\n\nWriting the cluster query...\n\nNow I'm looking at the searchUsers query more carefully — it groups events by resolved_id and applies pagination, but I'm concerned about whether ClickHouse supports ILIKE operations on coalesced columns.\n\nActually, I think I can use a subquery approach to handle this. I'll wrap the grouped results so I can filter on the resolved_id alias using ILIKE in the outer query, then apply the cursor-based pagination.\n\nAlternatively, the HAVING clause should work just fine for filtering on the grouped alias and applying the string pattern matching along with the cursor comparison.\n\nNow I'm setting up the test file for the query generation. I'll mock the ClickHouse client and verify it gets called with the right parameters rather than exporting the query builder itself. For the search filter test, I need to check that the query includes the ILIKE condition, and for pagination, I'll verify the cursor condition is present.\n\nWriting test file... I could export a `buildSearchUsersQuery` function like the funnels tests do, or just inspect the mock's call arguments to check the query string. I'll go with capturing the query from `mockQuery.mock.calls[0][0].query` since that's more direct. Now I'm planning out the actual test implementations, starting with checking that the returned users have the right fields, then verifying the query filtering and pagination logic.\n\nWriting test cases... Writing test cases... Writing test cases for getUserProfile... Writing test assertions... I'm realizing that ClickHouse returns a single row with NULL values when aggregating over an empty result set, so I need to check if `first_seen` is null to detect when a user profile doesn't exist. I'll use that as my \"not found\" indicator rather than checking the array length, and then implement the actual `getUserProfile` function with the stats query as the first step.\n\nNow I'm deciding between importing the events query from the identity module versus inlining it directly in users.ts—importing would require mocking two modules in tests, but inlining avoids that complexity. I'll go with inlining the events query to keep the test setup simpler.\n\nImplementing getUserProfile with inline events query... I'm realizing the `groupUniqArray` approach has issues with NULL values, so I'm going to split this into three separate queries instead—one for stats like first and last seen timestamps, another to get the distinct user and device IDs in the identity cluster, and a third for the actual events, keeping each query focused and testable.\n\nSetting up the mock calls...\n\nWriting the implementation... I'm defining the search function that queries users with optional filtering by name and pagination support, setting a reasonable limit cap and building dynamic SQL conditions based on the provided parameters. Writing database queries... Executing the second query to fetch the identity cluster, then extracting the unique user and device IDs from the results before moving on to query the actual events. I'm finishing up the response object with the resolved identity, first and last seen timestamps, the identity cluster containing all linked user and device IDs, and the events list. Now I'm reconsidering whether the `searchUsers` query can properly use the `resolved_id` alias in the HAVING clause—ClickHouse does support referencing SELECT aliases in HAVING after GROUP BY, so that approach should work.\n\nFor the limit parameter, I'm following the existing pattern where it's passed as a number in the query params and used with the `{limit:UInt64}` placeholder in the query. Now I'm setting up the test assertions to verify the query filter behavior.\n\nWriting test cases... Writing route tests...\n\nI need to understand how Next.js 16 handles dynamic route parameters since the docs mention breaking changes—the params might be a Promise that needs to be awaited, which is different from